##174 people infected: A week in Sea Quarantine for Japan's luxury cruise ships

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

On Feb. 5, more than 3,600 people aboard the diamond princess in Yokohama, Japan, were quarantined for 14 days after a passenger on board was found to have a new coronavirus infection. As of Feb. 12,174 people had been confirmed infected on the ship, far exceeding the total number of confirmed infections in Japan, and the diamond princess incident has become the largest cluster of infections outside mainland China. After nearly a week of quarantine, the increased number of infections, and the possibility of extended quarantine, are becoming a growing concern for the people on board.

Intern reporters | Zhang Jieqiong and Li Xiaojie

The "terror cruise" in quarantine

At eight o 'clock on the morning of February 7, Taylor stood in front of the cabin balcony and looked out the window. The diamond princess had been docked for four days, but passengers were still unable to disembark. Two military trucks and five ambulances were parked in the harbor, and Japanese men in camouflage stood by the hatch. The passenger, who had been diagnosed with the new coronavirus, stepped off the ship with the medics in white protective suits and entered the compartment. As passengers were being whisked away in the corridors, Taylor grew nervous. "It's like a hunger game. I'm not sure who's going to get caught next. "

The "terror cruise" in quarantine

At eight o 'clock on the morning of February 7, Taylor stood in front of the cabin balcony and looked out the window. The diamond princess had been docked for four days, but passengers were still unable to disembark. Two military trucks and five ambulances were parked in the harbor, and Japanese men in camouflage stood by the hatch. The passenger, who had been diagnosed with the new coronavirus, stepped off the ship with the medics in white protective suits and entered the compartment. As passengers were being whisked away in the corridors, Taylor grew nervous. "It's like a hunger game. I'm not sure who's going to get caught next. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On Feb. 3, the diamond princess arrived in Yokohama, Japan, ahead of schedule. Medical staff quarantined all passengers on board. On Feb. 5, Japanese health authorities ordered all passengers on board the ship to be quarantined and not to leave the cabin because 10 new coronavirus infections were found in 31 samples.

On February 10, the number of confirmed cases on board reached 135, including one from mainland China, three from Hong Kong and one from Taiwan, 73 Japanese, 25 Americans, 11 Australians, 8 Filipinos, 8 Canadians, 2 Ukrainians, 1 Briton, 1 Argentine and 1 New Zealander. As of the morning of February 12, the number of cruise ship infections had risen to 174, including a quarantine officer who was on board to receive and send passenger health questionnaires. The number of people infected on board far exceeds the total number of confirmed cases in Japan, and the diamond princess incident has become the largest cluster of infections outside mainland China.

The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, which is responsible for responding to the outbreak on board the ship, said on Feb. 10 that 336 people had been screened for the virus and that the government would consider targeting all passengers and crew members in response to the concerns of the Japanese people, upon their disembarkation at the end of the quarantine period on 19 February, a complete test for the new coronavirus was carried out. Prior to that, screening was conducted primarily in close contact with those who had previously been identified as infected. On the 12th, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare said that high risk groups on board the ship, such as the elderly, could be removed from the ship and transferred to hospitals in Japan for observation and treatment. In addition, it is not known whether the 14-day isolation period for other personnel will be recalculated after new infections are detected on a daily basis.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Taylor and Rachel, a newly married couple from North Texas, were due to end their honeymoon cruise on Feb. 4. But now they are stuck with 2,664 other passengers and 1,045 crew. Passengers confirmed to be infected will be taken off the ship and taken to a local hospital in Yokohama for observation. Seeing the passengers separated from their families, Taylor made a vow of true love: "I just hope we don't split up. As long as we can stay together in the cabin, we'll try to be happy. "

Taylor lived in a balcony cabin, the most luxurious of the three on board, with windows and balconies, and was free to enjoy the sun during his isolation. In the afternoon, he received messages from friends in Australia who told him their test results were negative, and Taylor was relieved to learn that the Australians had been sitting next to him and his wife for two weeks at dinner.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The diamond princess is one of the best honeymooners in the world, with 1,337 cabins and 748 private balconies on one of the world's 15 most luxurious cruises. With a total volume of more than three "titanic, " the 18-story building is packed with entertainment, bars, theaters, a library and even a wedding hall. If the original route had been followed from Yokohama on January 20, to Kagoshima on January 22, to Hong Kong on January 25, and then to Da Nang, Ha Long Bay, Geelong, Okinawa, Shizuoka, finally docked at Yokohama on February 4th.

The 15 day trip, which cost more than 15,000 yuan, was enough for Taylor and Rachel to Bond. It was only on board that Taylor realized that, as a young American couple, he and his wife were definitely in the minority. Because most of the cruise ship is the old age but the vitality of the elderly, they walk on Deck, Hall, the cruise ship is both spacious and peaceful.

A Journey that never ends

She was among the first passengers on board to be aware of the outbreak, and before boarding she had seen online news of the five confirmed cases of COVID-19. The seven members of the family still boarded the ship on Jan. 25 as planned, but 15 pairs of face masks were added to their luggage, she told the economist.

A Journey that never ends

She was among the first passengers on board to be aware of the outbreak, and before boarding she had seen online news of the five confirmed cases of COVID-19. The seven members of the family still boarded the ship on Jan. 25 as planned, but 15 pairs of face masks were added to their luggage, she told the economist.

But six days later, on Feb. 1, she came across news that an 80-year-old Hong Kong man had been aboard the diamond princess before being diagnosed with a new coronavirus infection. According to the news, the old man developed a cough on January 19, boarded a cruise ship from Yokohama on January 20, passed through Kagoshima on the 22nd, got off the ship with 40 other people and took a bus tour, and arrived in Hong Kong on the 25th, the 30-year-old man began to develop symptoms of fever and was admitted to a Hong Kong hospital for isolation and treatment.

Huang Yaxin told this magazine, she immediately put down the phone, put on a mask, rushed to the customer service room to ask. The crew told her that the Hong Kong government had informed the ship that only one of the guests had been diagnosed, and that those who showed signs of fever or flu would be quarantined. "I'll let you know if I hear anything, " she said.

In those days, Wang Minmin, a Chinese sailor, also heard news of the outbreak from friends in China. When she learned of an infection on board, she went to the cruise clinic to ask for some masks, but that was not enough to give her a sense of security. The other crew members met in the corridor and spoke to her openly. "VIRUS! Virus! " More than 1,000 crew members were shouted at her jokingly, Wang told this newspaper, twenty of them are from China, and the rest are mostly Southeast Asians. Wang estimates that he has to deal with at least 500 people a day, and that there may be an incubation period.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Indian crew on board

The quarantine was ordered step by step. On the afternoon of February 3, Liao Fang heard on the radio that the cruise ship would arrive in Yokohama ten hours early. Liao Fang told our reporter that she listened to the radio carefully every time because the eight old people in her group could not understand Japanese and English. When the broadcast ended, the ship was once again buzzing with laughter from the passengers at the indoor swimming pool, playing Mahjong and cards around the square table, and Japanese passengers, as Akita Prefecture passed by, took out their cell phones, took a photo and posted it on their twitter account; In the lounge next to the main hall, a dozen old men sat on Tan leather couches, passing microphones one by one. A white-haired man requested a Japanese song.

At 8:45 p.m. , there will be a musical at the ship's theater. Nearly half the audience was seated half an hour before the show began. Before the Red Curtains were drawn, cheerful music played back and forth in the hall, and people talked with their heads pressed together in order to hear each other clearly. At the same time, the Japanese health bureau quarantine personnel dressed up in masks, protective clothing, is coming to the giant ship.

At night, starting from the top floor, the quarantine officers enter the cabin one by one, pressing the ear thermometer button against the passenger's ear. Passengers with a health test card, fever, cold, runny nose are checked no, the quarantine officers will leave. But others needed further tests. At 4:30 in the morning, Huang's family was awakened again. The quarantine officers took swabs from the throat swabs of three people. Huang's husband was listed as the first batch of 273 samples because he had seen the ship's doctor, of the 273,153 had close contact with elderly Hong Kong men, and 120 developed fever and cough.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Passengers on board

Quarantine work continued throughout the day. Early in the morning on February 5th, the radio went up, but it wasn't a drop-off notice. The captain said, tiredly, that quarantine was still going on and that 10 of the 31 samples that had been sent over had been confirmed as infected. The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare ordered that all passengers be quarantined for 14 days.

The News of isolation is like a stone falling on the surface of calm water. A passenger opened a new twitter account and changed his name to "sequestered on the Diamond Princess" , sending out the first message. Liao Fang and her family immediately put on the mask. Before she boarded the ship in Hong Kong, she took her temperature and put it away. Now, she put it back on.

Starting Feb. 5, crew member Roth will be required to wear gloves and face masks throughout the day, carry dinner plates from the kitchen to the cabin hallway and place them one by one on the cabin door sill, in a series of repetitions that will begin at 6:30 a.m. and last for 13 hours, before that, he only had to work ten hours. He recalled returning to his six-square-meter crew cabin to rest after work on the evening of April 4. "The ship just docked at Yokohama. I fell asleep. Everything was fine. I definitely didn't expect to wake up in quarantine the next day. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Roth said he used to have a beer every day after work at the crew bar. After the quarantine had begun, the bars and casinos were closed, and Roth was alone on deck, breathing the fresh air, eating and smoking a cigarette. The night was cold, and the sea breeze made Roth Shiver. "It's all more chaotic. I wouldn't say I'm a waiter now, I'm more like a nurse, or a prison guard, eating out of a prisoner's cell. "

Looking back, Liao Fang was so hopeful that Feb. 3 would have been her last night on the ship, a night that would have been the perfect end to her journey. The yellow roof of the cafeteria lights up the tawny table, giving the hall its splendor. Dinner guests sat together, and at each of the four entrances a uniformed crew member said, wash your hands before you eat, in a soft voice, as each passenger entered. "Wash for at least 20 seconds, " read a frayed piece of paper in the front corner of the dish, and passengers waited patiently, one by one. Late at night, the restaurant manager and the entire staff line up and occupy the corridor, raising their hands and waving their handkerchiefs in unison as they bid farewell to the passengers.

And now, with the full stop being an Ellipsis, they face a long period of isolation.

"Not too bad. "

In the first few days of isolation, the room's catering department was scrambling, and passengers often woke up hungry but still couldn't wait for lunch. "I dream of being woken up by room service and then going to bed, " said Japanese passenger Ishihara. All this time, she felt her ears tense, and she could catch the slightest sound outside the cabin. One day, there was a crackling sound of boiled eggs. She trotted excitedly to the door and opened it. The waiting waiter did not appear.

"Not too bad. "

In the first few days of isolation, the room's catering department was scrambling, and passengers often woke up hungry but still couldn't wait for lunch. "I dream of being woken up by room service and then going to bed, " said Japanese passenger Ishihara. All this time, she felt her ears tense, and she could catch the slightest sound outside the cabin. One day, there was a crackling sound of boiled eggs. She trotted excitedly to the door and opened it. The waiting waiter did not appear.

After being quarantined, Matthew Smith continued to punch in on Three Meals a Day, scrambled eggs, hamburgers, croissants in the morning, and Natto Rice at noon, "The only thing we can do now is not to think about how much time we have left. As long as you accept every day, every second, it's not too bad. "

Ms. Akino, whose daughter works on a cruise ship, asks what she wants to eat and sends it to her. "I just want a cup of Ramen, because there's no time to eat slowly, " she replied. Like Roth, Ms. Akino's daughter works 13 hours a day, with only an hour of rest between.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The cleaning also bothered the people on the boat. Unexpectedly, Ishihara, who uses a cleaning robot to clean her room at home, now cleans her cabin on the luxury liner. From the drainpipe to the red carpet, she had to scrub them down with detergent. Tired from the heavy cleaning work, she made up her mind to bring a vacuum next time on the boat.

Huang Yaxin lives with her husband and son in a 10-square-meter cabin with no windows or balconies. The night before, she had been worried about the health of her family, Mom, Dad, aunt, uncle, and her companions, all quarantined in the other two cabins. "I was miserable about not being able to go out and breathe fresh air, and I wanted to cry, " Huang told the magazine. Early on the morning of February 7th, "We have consulted with the health department and decided to give every guest a regular time to move around, " she said, wakened by the ship's announcement. After 72 hours in the cabin, Huang and her family were finally allowed to do so, move to the deck for 60 Minutes.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Boarded the deck of the moment, Huang Yaxin and his family finally ushered in the long-awaited fresh air. The Sea Sunshine is not very dazzling, the sea breeze gently blowing, no longer as the previous days as cold. Mom, Dad, aunt and uncle separated by a meter, they wear masks, standing on the deck, writhing hips, stretching limbs. The son told Huang Yaxin that this was the best day of his life.

On the morning of February 8th, the diamond princess was relaunched, heading offshore. At 9:26, when the Horn sounded, Ishihara looked out the window and saw the ship moving away from the Yokohama Bay Bridge, and Mount Fuji Shrinking in the distance. "Farewell to Mount Fuji, " she wrote. "I hope it will not be forever. ".

Unknown risks

"No food, no medicine, no phone call. I fell asleep, " Ishihara tweeted on Feb. 9, when she learned of the latest Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare statistics, the number of new coronavirus infections confirmed by cruise ships increased by six, bringing the total to 70.

Unknown risks

"No food, no medicine, no phone call. I fell asleep, " Ishihara tweeted on Feb. 9, when she learned of the latest Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare statistics, the number of new coronavirus infections confirmed by cruise ships increased by six, bringing the total to 70.

February 9 was also Liao Fang's most anxious day on the boat. Eight of the 14 people she was traveling with were elderly, and four days ago, after writing their names on the drug register, the aunts and uncles never got their medicine. Liao Fang called the information desk and was told that the medicine had arrived but was still being sorted. On the other hand, suffering from diabetes, heart disease uncle and aunt can not wait, Liao Fang anxious in the cabin around. As an exporter in a foreign trade company, she was used to dealing with urgent matters, but this was the first time she felt that she was in control of a matter of life and death. Liao Fang tried everything. At 11 o'clock the night before, she was still asking for help from the Hong Kong Immigration Department. She was told that after purchasing drugs, they would be sent to the ship for approval.

Passengers hit out "medicine is not enough" for help cloth

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the dock, medical supplies from the Japanese government have arrived. "The Japanese government is providing additional manpower support to our ships and crew, including 7,000 respirators and a professional medical team of 16 doctors, 12 nurses and medical receptionists, " The ship's cruise company said in a statement. "We are also providing medicine to guests in need. So far we have received about 2,000 applications for the supply of medicines. These applications will be prioritised according to need and urgency."

Speculation about how the virus will spread is also rife. Gaye Kut was an American novelist who solved a murder on another cruise ship. Now, isolated on the diamond princess, she is trying to solve another mystery: "although the crew wore rubber gloves, they are trying to protect the passengers, but there is no scientific evidence that the virus can not be transmitted through them. "

After a day's work, Wang returned to the third floor of her cabin, where the crew kept the ship afloat below sea level. Wang and a Filipino were crammed into a bunk-bed cabin, which contained nothing but beds. When she turned on the cabin air conditioning, she vaguely remembered reading about the SARS virus in which central air conditioning had increased the spread of the virus. The more she thought about it, the more she feared, "we're not being quarantined, we're waiting to be infected. "

A US passenger called the US Embassy in Japan to express the same concern as Ms Wang. On Feb. 9,428 American passengers on the ship received a letter from officials at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, which said the center "currently has no evidence of virus transmission through the air-handling system from room to room on the ship. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The receiving line was finally established. On Feb. 9, Ishihara's family dragged her suitcase to the dock, and they brought her medicine, instant noodles, and cleaning supplies. Everything brought to Ishihara had to be checked before it went on board. Ishihara stood on the balcony and watched from a distance, she talks to her family on her cell phone, trying to wave at them. "I can't help but think of that documentary I saw recently about the Berlin Wall, " Ishihara said.

The good news and the bad news always arrive alternately on a cruise ship. On the morning of the 10th, the Cruise Company has just announced that it will refund passengers the full cost of the cruise, including hotel and air fare. In the evening, it was announced that the number of confirmed cases had reached 135 and that 65 more patients would be taken off the ship the next day.

At six o'clock on the morning of the 11th, Liao Fang got up early. She fell asleep the night before after receiving a phone call confirming that the last of her peers had got their medicine. Over 1,000 doses of medicine have been distributed on the ship. Liao Fang stepped onto the balcony to stretch herself. On the dock, more than 40 ambulances lined up in three rows, sirens ringing in the air, and people were being ferried out of the constructed tunnels, wrapped tightly in protective clothing. These days, Liao Fang is used to this kind of scene.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Early in the morning, the captain's voice came as expected: "Good Morning, we are ready to meet the challenges of the day, strong and united. ". The diamond princess will set sail around 12:00, heading southeast to collect water and dump trash. The water shouldn't be that bad this time. Let's solve this day together."

On that day, Liao Fang learned that 10 of the 135 confirmed infected were crew members. She called the Chinese Embassy in Japan and told them that she wanted to go home to quarantine, and that every day that passed on the boat was more dangerous. Wang Minmin is on the phone, waiting for passengers at any time call, the towel sent to the cabin. She had a phone call of her own, and she couldn't get it out.

In recent days, she had seen nothing but information about the passengers, and she thought the 20 Chinese workers on board were as invisible as the hull of a ship hidden below sea level. "I want everyone to know that we exist, that our employees can move around freely in the cabin, that we can get together in the elevator, that we can sit face to face with dozens of people when we eat. Now I can't even go on the deck, " Wang said. This call, she also want to call the embassy, but her hand still did not press the dial button, she was afraid of "call no answer, the last way is also blocked. ".

As dusk approached, all 65 new confirmed cases of infection were taken off the ship. At last the great ship began to move again, and the waves were still, and the diamond princess rocked out to sea. Unlike three days ago, there were 45 more doctors, 55 more nurses and 45 more pharmacists on board. Two coast guard boats followed, marking two white lines across the blue water.

(pseudonyms include Liao Fang, Wang Minmin, Roth, Akita Prefecture and Ishihara)
